  "doc_id": "43654",
  "text": "The most common DDDIs in previous studies have been associated with the use of anticoagulants, [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] potassium-sparing diuretics, potassium supplements, or angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) inhibitors, [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] aspirin with other NSAIDs [CITATION_7] and carbamazepine with various drugs. [CITATION_8] Our findings confirm that the concomitant use of potassium-sparing diuretics and potassium supplements are common DDDIs. Among concomitant users of potassium Inhibition of CYP2D6 catalysed morphine formation from codeine by duloxetine. In clinical studies codeine increased the threshold of experimental pain in extensive metabolisers of CYP2D6 but not of poor metabolisers lacking the activation process. Similarly, the CYP2D6 inhibitor quinidine decreased morphine formation from codeine and reduced the analgesic effect and abuse liability of codeine. Duloxetine is a moderate CYP2D6 inhibitor. The effect of duloxetine on the pharmacokinetics or pharmacodynamics of codeine has not been studied, but it is likely that duloxetine reduces the analgesic effect of codeine in a similar way as other CYP2D6 inhibitors.",
